<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
    <a href="/backlog/1565/">#1565</a> turns a user ruling — <strong>&ldquo;dev-tools belong in Plateau, not
    FUI&rdquo;</strong> — into a precise, codifiable placement rule across the constellation:
    <strong>WE</strong> (the standard / contracts, zero implementation), <strong>Frontier UI</strong> (the
    reference <em>implementation</em> of the standards), <strong>Plateau</strong> (the <em>product</em> layer).
    The ruling is not free-standing: it collides with two <em>ratified</em> placements —
    <a href="/backlog/809/">#809</a> (the block-explorer workbench is FUI-owned) and the
    reproduction-conformance program <a href="/backlog/1225/">#1225</a> (&ldquo;the deterministic diff engine
    is <strong>FUI</strong> (impl/devtool)&rdquo;) — and a blanket &ldquo;move every tool to Plateau&rdquo;
    reading would also drag WE&rsquo;s own conformance verifiers (<a href="/backlog/1467/">#1467</a>) out of the
    standard layer. So the open question is the <em>exact cut</em>, not the direction.
</p>

<h2>The load-bearing finding — the dividing line is the consumer</h2>
<p>
    Five external precedents were surveyed, and they converge on one principle that <strong>matches the
    project&rsquo;s own ratified <code>project_conformance_verifier_vs_subject</code> (#1467) exactly</strong>: a
    surface a <strong>human operates</strong> (workbench / inspector / configurator) is a developer
    <strong>product</strong>, separate from the implementation it inspects; a tool that <strong>reads an
    implementation&rsquo;s observable output as DATA</strong> (a conformance verifier) is <strong>machinery that
    lives with the standard</strong>. &ldquo;The inspector is not the thing inspected.&rdquo;
</p>

<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Precedent</th><th>Arrangement</th><th>Transferable principle</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Chrome DevTools vs Blink/V8</strong></td>
            <td>DevTools is a separate web app (own repo, builds without the engine); talks to the engine only over
                the CDP protocol (JSON commands out, JSON events back).</td>
            <td><strong>The inspector is not the thing inspected.</strong> A human-operated surface observes the
                impl&rsquo;s output over a contract; it never <em>is</em> the impl.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Storybook vs the component library vs Chromatic</strong></td>
            <td>Storybook is a dev-dependency &ldquo;frontend workshop&rdquo; operating <em>on</em> your components
                (they live in your repo); Chromatic is the same team&rsquo;s commercial cloud product consuming the
                <strong>story</strong> format.</td>
            <td>OSS dev-tool + commercial product layered over a stable format — exactly the open-core
                WE/FUI/Plateau shape. The tool is separate from its subject; the format is the only lock.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Material Web / Theme Builder / m3.material.io</strong></td>
            <td>Three distinct homes: the components, a configurator that <strong>emits tokens as data</strong>, and
                the docs/spec site. The token namespace is the contract.</td>
            <td>A configurator emits <strong>config as data</strong> which the impl consumes — zero lock-in, lives in
                the tooling/product layer, not the component library.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>WPT reftests / testharness / Test262</strong></td>
            <td>Conformance suites live <strong>with the standard</strong> (tc39, web-platform-tests orgs), shared by
                every implementation; they read observable output as <strong>data</strong> (rendered pixels, a
                PASS/FAIL enum, behavioral asserts) and never embed engine internals.</td>
            <td><strong>A verifier that reads output as data is conformance machinery — it pairs with the standard,
                not the product.</strong> This <em>is</em> #1467 / WPT, externally confirmed.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Monorepo packages-vs-apps</strong> (Radix, MUI, Chakra, shadcn, Turborepo, Nx)</td>
            <td>The publishable <strong>library</strong> is the packages/libs layer; every <strong>deployable
                surface that consumes it</strong> — docs, playground, Storybook, tooling, CLIs — is the apps layer.
                (Turborepo: &ldquo;Library Packages … aren&rsquo;t independently deployable&rdquo;; Nx 80/20.)</td>
            <td>Developer tooling and product surfaces are <strong>apps-layer (&rarr; Plateau)</strong>, structurally
                separated from the reference library (<strong>&rarr; FUI</strong>). Naming varies; the split holds.</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h2>The synthesized cut (the consumer/embed test, to ratify in #1565)</h2>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Reads an implementation&rsquo;s observable output as DATA</strong> (verifier / golden-vector /
        trace) &rarr; <strong>conformance machinery &rarr; stays WE</strong> (per #1467, WPT/Test262).
        <em>Untouched by the new ruling.</em></li>
    <li><strong>Build-time implementation transform / reference-impl generator</strong> (codegen, CSS lowering,
        bundler plugins) &rarr; <strong>impl &rarr; stays FUI</strong> (per impl-is-not-a-standard #020/#291).
        <em>Untouched.</em></li>
    <li><strong>Developer-operated surface you run against your OWN build</strong> (workbench, inspector, explorer
        CLI chrome, configurator, dev-panel) &rarr; <strong>product tooling &rarr; Plateau.</strong>
        <em>This is the ruling&rsquo;s target.</em></li>
    <li><strong>Ships embedded on THIRD-PARTY / customer sites as a distribution/showcase of the impl</strong>
        &rarr; <strong>FUI distribution</strong> (Plateau-routing would re-introduce the cross-origin boundary
        #809 dissolved). <em>The #809 carve-out.</em></li>
</ol>

<h2>How the survey + skeptics reshaped the forks</h2>
<p>
    Three throwaway skeptics attacked the initial defaults; <strong>two flipped</strong> — the expected outcome
    of a real attack, not a rubber-stamp:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Fork 1 (the rule) — SURVIVES-WITH-AMENDMENT.</strong> The initial 3-way sort <em>relisted settled
        law</em> (#1467, impl-is-not-a-standard) as if the ruling needed it, diluting a clear directive. Amended to
        ONE positive test (operated-surface &rarr; Plateau) plus the third-party-embed carve-out, citing the
        existing rules as <em>unchanged</em>.</li>
    <li><strong>Fork 2 (block-explorer #809) — FLIPPED to carve-OUT.</strong> The #809 driver is
        <em>third-party-site embedding</em>; &ldquo;Plateau renders FUI same-origin&rdquo; is <strong>false</strong>
        for the customer-site case — it re-introduces the very cross-origin boundary #809 dissolved. The
        block-explorer is &ldquo;reference-impl that only looks like tooling.&rdquo; It <strong>stays FUI</strong>;
        #809 is the cited precedent, <em>not</em> reversed.</li>
    <li><strong>Fork 3 (explorer) — FLIPPED to split.</strong> The explorer&rsquo;s Layer-1/Layer-2 oracles
        <strong>read output as data</strong> and Layer-2 drives WE conformance vectors through FUI bindings (the
        runtime half of #899/#1467 machinery) &mdash; moving them to Plateau is inconsistent with the refined rule.
        Split: conformance harness stays FUI, vision (Layer-3) stays Plateau (no-leakage #475), only the product
        CLI chrome &rarr; Plateau.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    Net: the user&rsquo;s ruling <strong>stands and is honored</strong> (every human-operated surface you run
    against your own build moves to Plateau), but it is a <em>refinement</em> of the constellation-placement
    statute, not a wholesale override — disturbing neither #1467 (verifiers), impl-is-not-a-standard (codegen),
    nor #809 (the third-party-embed carve-out).
</p>

